😳 There are so many myths about life insurance & it’s time to address them. 

🥴 Myth 1: Life insurance is only for healthy, middle-aged adults.
✅ Fact: You are never too old or too young to purchase life insurance. It’s true that your costs will increase as you age and that people with illnesses or certain risk factors may pay more, but there are options available for everyone.

🥴 Myth 2: I’m single or married with no children, so I don’t need life insurance.
✅ Fact: Your loved ones can use life insurance benefits to pay off your debts, including student loans, mortgages, and car loans. It can also be used to take care of your final expenses, such as burial.

🥴 Myth 3: I cannot afford life insurance.
✅ Fact: Consumers often overestimate the cost of a term life insurance policy. Many individuals are surprised to learn that a healthy 30-year-old could potentially get a $100,000 30-year level term policy for just $40 a month. With this policy, beneficiaries would receive the full $100,000 (as most are tax-free) if they were to pass away between 30 and 60.

While I’m not telling you which type of life insurance policy to get, I’m telling you to know the difference between the many options AND I’m telling you to have something. 

To keep it simple, Term Life Insurance is more affordable than Whole Life Insurance. When an agent sells a Whole Life Insurance policy, they’re banking possibly a minimum $400 for a product that MAY not meet the needs of your family. 

Term insurance last for a max of 30-35 years based on your location & age. Whole life policies last up to 99 years but are often times triple the amount you’d pay for a Term Life Insurance Policy. 

The main disadvantage to whole life policies are the premium rate & if you take your money out of the “savings portion”, you’re charged 8% interest. If the customer doesn’t pay it back, the death claim is reduced for your family. 

The main disadvantage for a term policy is you do need a medical for anything over $300k, you’re covered for up to 35 years (in some states)

We’d love to share more facts for you.
